Hey Lila,

My advice on design trends: most of them look cool for a reason=E2=80=A6
BUT, if you follow them too closely, your design will probably
look dated sooner.

I was recently updating my UI Inspiration Folder, and noticed
that the Starlight website (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/8kunv6762kfoh0xw6nnak/dpheh0hqxonl70tm/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3RhcmxpZ2h0Lm1vbmV5Lw=3D=3D
) has no fewer than 6 trendy UI motifs from the last year or so.
(It also looks really cool! =F0=9F=98=8E)

So let=E2=80=99s cover those today, including:

* The trendy element
* Tips for re-creating it
* What you could vary to not be too faddy

[=F0=9F=93=A3 Announcement: Learn UI Design (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/8kunv6762kfoh0xw6nnak/7qh7h8h0e65r4wuz/aH=
R0cHM6Ly9sZWFybnVpLmRlc2lnbg=3D=3D
) and Learn UX Design (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/8kunv6762kfoh0xw6nnak/z2hghnhozkxqd0sp/aH=
R0cHM6Ly9sZWFybnV4LmRlc2lnbg=3D=3D
) open for new enrollments in one week. Join thousands of
students in leveling up your design skills =F0=9F=8E=89=F0=9F=91=8D]

Here=E2=80=99s the site, if you want to go trend-hunting first =F0=9F=98=89

=E2=80=8B

**********************
1/ Perspective Imagery
**********************

I will die on the hill of =E2=80=9Cthe harder it is to do in Figma, the
cooler it looks=E2=80=9D.

The price of rectangles is low because the supply is HUGE. But
add a little 3-D effect and all of a sudden, the design POPS =F0=9F=92=85

This makes Starlight=E2=80=99s fairly ho-hum account cards really shine!

=E2=80=8B
But! Re-creating this effect maaay not require any fancy 3D
work =E2=80=93 if you use the Figma plugin Perspective Toolkit (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/8kunv6762kfoh0xw6nnak/x0hph6hnmp057oc5/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmlnbWEuY29tL2NvbW11bml0eS9wbHVnaW4vODYyMDU5NjYzNjg5NzgwOTQz
) (which is frustratingly unintuitive =F0=9F=98=A1 =E2=80=93 yet free =F0=
=9F=98=81).

A couple of lighting effects add some extra pop. Here=E2=80=99s the
step-by-step:

=E2=80=8B
You can check out this Figma (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/8kunv6762kfoh0xw6nnak/e0hph7hkzlo8nof8/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmlnbWEuY29tL2ZpbGUvOENHa2RpbWdaU0ZobnlWYmxwYjNlYi9FdmVyeS0yM=
DIzLXRyZW5kP25vZGUtaWQ9MTE3JTNBODg=3D
) for exact shadow values =F0=9F=98=89

***************
2/ Bento Layout
***************

This technique has been around for a while, but is really gaining
some steam lately =F0=9F=92=AA

Whenever you have a bunch of elements (let=E2=80=99s say 5+) that you
want to present as a unified group, try putting them in a =E2=80=9Cbento=E2=
=80=9D
(referencing the Japanese divided lunchbox style).

=E2=80=8B
Apple is the master of this (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/8kunv6762kfoh0xw6nnak/7qh7h8h0e65r47bz/aH=
R0cHM6Ly9hcHBsZS1zdW1tYXJ5LXNsaWRlcy52ZXJjZWwuYXBwL2V2ZW50LUFwcGxlRXZlbnRTZ=
XB0ZW1iZXIyMDIy
), and they demonstrate one of the most important lessons of
bento layout (and UI design in general): use the best imagery you
can.

Note the high-quality photography, eye-popping gradient effects,
and thoughtful arrangement of elements.

**************************
3/ Backlit Section Divider
**************************

It=E2=80=99s become more common to see =E2=80=9Cbacklighting=E2=80=9D in da=
rk modes =E2=80=93
which usually takes the form of a large radial gradient that
represents a slightly illuminated surface.

=E2=80=8B
Here, two large sections are divided by a backlit container.

Where might you use this? Anywhere you have a lot of whitespace
or a divider line! (but try to explore more options too =E2=80=93 e.g.
textures, imagery appearing under the bottom panel, etc =F0=9F=91=8D)

You might need to squint for this one. It's worth it though.

******************
3 trends, 1 screen
******************

You don=E2=80=99t even have to scroll to see a bunch of the trendy
elements on the Starlight page:

* The super quirky serif headline
* The pill-shaped =E2=80=9Cannouncement=E2=80=9D widget
* The subtle grid of rectangles

=E2=80=8B
But while these trends are great to know about, most will come
and go.

The most important part is the underlying principles, the craft,
the techniques that don=E2=80=99t change every couple years.

And those are the bedrock of Learn UI Design (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/8kunv6762kfoh0xw6nnak/7qh7h8h0e65r4wuz/aH=
R0cHM6Ly9sZWFybnVpLmRlc2lnbg=3D=3D
) and Learn UX Design (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/8kunv6762kfoh0xw6nnak/z2hghnhozkxqd0sp/aH=
R0cHM6Ly9sZWFybnV4LmRlc2lnbg=3D=3D
). Stuff like:

* How lighting and shadows can be used on different interface
elements (Learn UI Design, lesson 2.7)
* The major ways designing in dark mode differs from light mode
(Learn UI Design, lesson 3.8)
* How to use alignment and consistency to create great layouts
(Learn UI Design, lesson 2.2 and 2.4)

Or:

* What design patterns you can rely on vs. ignore (Learn UX
Design, unit 3)
* How to catch usability issues before they crop up in testing
(Learn UX Design, unit 2)
* How to stop biasing your user interviews (Learn UX Design,
lesson 4.1 and 4.2)

(The first 3 are Learn UI Design; the second 3 are Learn UX
Design)

